CQRS splits reads from writes because they have different needs. The write side owns invariants, needs the aggregate's full state to call decide, and lives behind the event store. The read side only needs a denormalised view shaped for a query, populated by a projection subscribed to the same events. If both sides shared a state type you would couple query response shape to aggregate internals, making both harder to evolve. Keeping them independent lets you spin up as many read models as you need per stream.

